"Abt 1316":"circa 1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","Abt 1294":"circa 1294","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1294–":"about 1294–Deceased","1294–Male":"1294–Deceased","1298–Female":"1298–Deceased","1317–1333":"1317–1333","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1382":"1382","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","Abt 1316":"about 1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","Abt 1294":"about 1294","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Preston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from one of the many places (most notably one in Lancashire) so called from Old English <i>prēost</i> ‘priest’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","occasionally from Middle English <i>prest</i> + <i>son</i> ‘son of the priest’. Priests were forbidden marriage but many produced illegitimate offspring."],"variants":[{"name":"Presson","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): variant of   Preston  .","French: occupational name for a presser of wine or oil, from a derivative of <i>presser</i> ‘to press’."]},{"name":"Prestwich","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place in Lancashire (now Greater Manchester), so called from Old English <i>prēost</i> ‘priest’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying settlement’, or from other places with the same derivation. Variants such as <i>Prestidge</i>, <i>Prestage</i>, etc., parallel the local pronunciation of the Lancashire name. Compare   Preston  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":21,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":34,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":43,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":88,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Preston was born about 1294, in Preston, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Adam Preston, was 36 and his mother, Mrs Adam Preston, was 26. He married Margaret Banastre about 1316, in Preston, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Preston, Lancashire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1294–":"umbes 1294–Surnud","1294–Male":"1294–Surnud","1298–Female":"1298–Surnud","1317–1333":"1317–1333","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1382":"1382","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","Abt 1316":"umbes 1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","Abt 1294":"umbes 1294","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1294–":"noin 1294–Kuollut","1294–Male":"1294–Kuollut","1298–Female":"1298–Kuollut","1317–1333":"1317–1333","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1382":"1382","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","Abt 1316":"noin 1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","Abt 1294":"noin 1294","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1294–":"environ 1294–Décédé","1294–Male":"1294–Décédé","1298–Female":"1298–Décédée","1317–1333":"1317–1333","1260–Male":"1260–Décédé","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1382":"1382","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","Abt 1316":"environ 1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","Abt 1294":"environ 1294","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert Preston est né environ 1294, à Preston, Lancashire, Angleterre, Roya